BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 190.8 720 Td (Chapter 1: The Night Sky) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (Maya loved spending summer evenings with her grandfather on the porch.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td (One clear night, the sky was filled with thousands of twinkling lights.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td ('Grandpa, what are those lights?' Maya asked, her eyes wide with wonder.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td ('Those are stars, Maya,' Grandpa smiled. 'Each one is a giant ball of burning gas.') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td (Maya could hardly believe it. Some of those tiny dots were bigger than our Sun!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td ('They look small because they are so incredibly far away,' Grandpa explained.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE OF STARS) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (Stars are enormous balls of hot gas, mostly hydrogen and helium.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (Deep inside a star, nuclear fusion smashes atoms together, releasing energy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (This energy is what makes stars shine so brightly across the universe.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Light travels at 186,000 miles per second, the fastest speed possible.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (A light-year is the distance light travels in one whole year - about 6 trillion miles!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 464 Td (Our nearest star \(besides the Sun\) is Proxima Centauri, 4.24 light-years away.) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 369 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 428 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 408 Td (* The Sun is a medium-sized star - some stars are 1,000 times bigger!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 390 Td (* You can see about 2,500 stars with your naked eye on a clear night.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 372 Td (* Stars appear to twinkle because Earth's atmosphere bends their light.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 339 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 323 Td (Go outside on a clear night and count the stars you can see. Try finding the Big Dipper!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 303 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 287 Td (If light takes 4 years to reach us from the nearest star, are we seeing it as it is NOW?) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
