BT 0 g /F2 20 Tf 186.0 720 Td (Chapter 4: Riding a Comet) Tj ET
q 0.5 G 1 w 72 710 m 540 710 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 680 Td (Suddenly, a brilliant streak of light zoomed past Maya's window!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 664 Td ('A comet!' she gasped. Without thinking, she jumped aboard for a ride.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 648 Td (The comet was like a giant dirty snowball, flying through space at incredible speed.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 632 Td (A glowing tail stretched behind them for millions of miles, shimmering in the sunlight.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 616 Td ('This is amazing!' Maya shouted. 'We are riding a piece of ancient history!') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 600 Td (The comet had been orbiting the Sun for billions of years, older than Earth itself.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 13 Tf 72 564 Td (THE SCIENCE OF COMETS) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 544 Td (Comets are made of ice, dust, and rock - often called 'dirty snowballs.') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 528 Td (They orbit the Sun in long, elliptical \(oval-shaped\) paths.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 512 Td (When a comet gets close to the Sun, the ice vaporizes creating a glowing tail.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 496 Td (Comet tails always point AWAY from the Sun, pushed by solar wind.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 480 Td (Halley's Comet visits Earth every 75-76 years \(next in 2061!\).) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 72 464 Td (Some comets take thousands of years to complete one orbit around the Sun.) Tj ET
q 0.92 g 67 379 478 89 re f Q
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 77 438 Td (SCIENCE FACT BOX) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 418 Td (* The word 'comet' comes from Greek meaning 'long-haired star.') Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 400 Td (* A comet's tail can stretch over 100 million miles long!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 382 Td (* Scientists think comets may have brought water to early Earth.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 349 Td (TRY THIS!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 10 Tf 82 333 Td (Make a comet: mix dirt, water, and dry ice \(with adult help\) to see it 'outgas'!) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F2 11 Tf 72 313 Td (THINK ABOUT IT:) Tj ET
BT 0.2 g /F4 10 Tf 82 297 Td (Why does a comet's tail always point away from the Sun, not behind it?) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
